I was curious whether corporate insiders reveal useful information through their SEC ownership filings.

First, I looked at what types of filings were most common. That helped me understand whether the dataset was mostly static ownership reports or actual changes in ownership.

Then I looked at which companies appeared most often. This showed that insider activity is not spread evenly across all companies.

Next, I compared acquisitions and dispositions. I expected insider buying to stand out, but the data showed that disposals were much more common.

That led me to ask whether transaction count was misleading. When I ranked companies and transactions by estimated dollar value, I found that a small number of high-value transactions dominated the dataset.

Finally, I looked at activity over time to see whether insider trading patterns changed by year.

The biggest lesson was that insider trading data cannot be interpreted at face value. Insider selling is common and may be routine, while insider buying may be a stronger signal because it is less frequent and more deliberate.